The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Special meet
                                                                                                               Special meet
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Bhubaneswar, Jan. 25: Fifteen-year-old Monica seemed oblivious to the crowd around her gaping at her and her poster on terrorism.        
	Busy adding paint to the picture, the differently-abled girls colourful protest against the vagaries of war and hate was a part of the National Abilympics Competition  the word Abilympics derived from two words, ability and Olympics. The teen was one of the 150 participants at the state-level talent hunt organised by Shanta Memorial Rehabilitation Centre in collaboration with the Centres Vocational Rehabilitation Centre for Handicapped. There were 24 events including computer programming, data processing, painting, poster designing, tailoring, pottery making, photography, electronic, furniture and jewellery making and wood carving competitions at the Abilympics.        
	Abilympics is to achieve a society where all kinds of people enjoy equal rights and opportunities, said Asha Hans, the executive vice-president of the centre. The Abilympics was first held in 1972 at Japan by the association for employment of the disabled under the ministry of labour. The aim was, and still is, to improve the vocational abilities of disabled persons.                                                                                                                                                                            
